It's also a great opportunity to spend some quality time with your friends, or even find new colleagues. I would really like to take part in it.
I know there are some people criticising trashing and I consider their arguments about littering. I wouldn't want to leave a mess behind me such as broken glass. I also wouldn't want to waste food. Some of British universities are known all over the world. Youth from many countries dreams about studying in Oxford or Cambridge, these cities are also visited by many tourists. What makes these universities so famous? One of the reasons is, of course, great level of education. But the other reason are unique traditions these schools celebrate.

Some of the traditions are about partying. When you're a student, every reason to party  is a good reason! At the beginning of the academic year Oxford university organize solemn marticulation at which freshers are officially becoming students. Everybody wears sub fuscs and gowns. But later there is also marticulash. This part is not solemn anymore, the students are partying and drinking alcohol. The other fun tradition is trashing. It takes part at the end of academic year, after the exams. Students celebrate a year of hard work by "trashing" their friends - throwing at them food, shaving foam and pouring champagne.

There are also traditions connected to how superstitious the British students are. At St. Andrews university people believe in bad luck such as failing the exams or loosing degree after committing "academic sins". One of the academic sins is stepping on the PH - initials of Patrick Hamilton on the ground in the place he was buried at the stake. Another sin is academic incest which is having sexual relationship with your academic family members (freshers receive academic parents who help them in their firsts weeks on the university). But there is one way to have your sins cleansed. You have to take a May dip. At the 1st of May, at the dawn, you have to take a bath in the sea. The water is freezing but it's worth it if you committed a sin!

There are many more interesting traditions at British universities. It's surprising how important they are for the students. I didn't expect them to care so much about traditions related to history or old superstitions.
